<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>The clinic will provide 1 500 patients with access to maternal and child care, dental care, TB and HIV/Aids care every month. Gauteng Premier David Makhura said the recent department of health report revealed that 71% of Gauteng clinics had achieved ideal clinic status – they opened on time, had good infrastructure, adequate supplies, were clean and staffed by healthcare professionals that practised the Batho Pele principles. Gauteng caters for over 20 million health-related visits a year – the biggest healthcare system in southern Africa – but despite improving access to healthcare services, a bigger need remains. This is why community-based healthcare is a way to address the needs of the people who currently don’t have access to basic, quality healthcare and in turn, facilitate community development. Philips and Rhiza launched the health clinic on wheels in 2015 to service Diepsloot and provide access to critical healthcare services. Three years since its start, the mobile clinic has grown. Every month, it serves 1 500 patients in Cosmo City and 1 500 in Diepsloot. The Mini-Community Life Centre, also in Diepsloot, directly services 25 000 people. “The mobile clinics have improved healthcare in some of our most vulnerable communities,” said Ntutule Tshenye, general manager of Philips South Africa. “The Orange Farm mobile clinic is the fifth project between Philips and Rhiza,” said Alef Meulenberg, Rhiza chairman.